              <otmi:snippet>Alternatively, interaction with Hbs1 or Dom34 might allow the ribosome itself to cleave the mRNA</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Both enzymes have similar roles in the other degradation pathways</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>But in other contexts, mRNA fragments stabilized by the absence of Xrn1 or the exosome are also heterogeneous </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>But other, perhaps more physiologically relevant, mRNAs with translational pause sites were much less subject to no-go decay</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>But the no-go decay pathway identified by Doma and Parker is different: this pathway begins its work in the middle of the mRNA ( Fig. 1 )</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>By contrast, mRNAs that entirely lack a translation stop site are subject to &quot;non-stop decay&quot; (reviewed in refs 2 , 3 )</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Cells alter their rates of mRNA transcription to change mRNA levels, and so rates of protein synthesis, in response to many stimuli</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Consistent with this possibility, in mice and fruitflies a mutation of a close relative of Dom34 called Pelota leads to specific defects in development and cell-cycle progression </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Doma and Parker ( page 561 of this issue) have discovered an mRNA quality-control system — &quot;no-go decay&quot; — with some unexpected features</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>During non-stop decay, Ski7 is proposed to release ribosomes stalled at the ends of mRNAs that lack a translation-termination site </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>For most human genes to be usefully expressed they must first be copied into messenger RNAs by the process of transcription</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Hbs1 is also related to a protein called Ski7 that is an accessory to the exosome </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>How the mRNA cleavage occurs in no-go decay has yet to be worked out</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>However, it seems likely that in other contexts this pathway will have been co-opted to regulate the abundance of specific mRNAs</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>However, the ends of the fragments that Doma and Parker detected following no-go cleavage were quite heterogeneous — more so than might be predicted by cleavage within the stalled ribosome</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In Doma and Parker&apos;s experiments, the no-go pathway is apparently acting specifically as a quality-control system</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In addition, cells must guard against the synthesis of abnormal mRNAs (surveillance), which can produce defective, potentially toxic, protein products</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In all organisms, the amount of each mRNA is very tightly controlled — a crucial step in the regulation of gene expression</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In each of these four pathways — at least in yeast — the mRNAs are degraded exclusively from their ends</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In either case, it would presumably be necessary to first remove the stalled ribosome, because inspection of the end points of the cleaved RNA does not show an obvious &quot;footprint&quot; — an area protected from cleavage by the bound ribosome</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In fact, different mRNAs differ radically in their rates of degradation, and this is subject to both metabolic and developmental regulation</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In fruitflies, recognition of mRNAs by the nonsense-mediated decay system also leads to their cleavage in the vicinity of the translation stop site </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In support of this, in the bacterium Escherichia coli pausing of translation can cause mRNA cleavage by the ribosome (at the &quot;A site&quot; of the ribosome) </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In this organism, two main pathways have been identified, each of which degrades the mRNA from only one of its ends — either the 5′ or the 3′ end</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>It is attractive to think that a similar mechanism might operate in yeast</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>It is not clear how widespread no-go decay is in yeast, or whether it is conserved in other animals</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>It may be that the main targets for no-go decay in the cell are chemically damaged mRNAs, which can cause a complete translation block </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>No-go degradation definitely requires stalling of the ribosome, because the termination of translation before the obstruction prevents cleavage of the mRNA </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Notably, Doma and Parker report substantial cleavage of mRNAs containing an artificial stem–loop structure that should create an almost impassable block for the ribosome</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Obvious possibilities are that Hbs1 or Dom34 catalyse it themselves, although their sequences do not suggest this, or they could recruit a specific nuclease enzyme to the site</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Ski7 is also needed when the exosome degrades the cleaved no-go mRNAs </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>So it could be that the free ends are nibbled away by other nucleases after the mRNAs have been cleaved by the ribosome</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>So it looks as though Dom34 and Hbs1 might interact with the stalled ribosome</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Such continuous surveillance to maintain high fidelity is metabolically expensive but, as elsewhere in life, infidelity is surely still more costly.</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The authors engineered an obstruction into mRNAs (a very stable &quot;stem–loop&quot; structure) to stall the translating ribosome, and showed that this triggered degradation</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The cleavage converts the mRNA into a non-stop transcript</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The fidelity of mRNA translation into protein is vital for the overall accuracy of gene expression, and cells have evolved ways to detect any aberrant mRNAs that have structural defects</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The initial cleavage of the mRNA involves two proteins called Dom34 and Hbs1</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The integrity and functionality of mRNAs are monitored by surveillance activities that act at many steps during the molecules&apos; nuclear maturation and cytoplasmic lifetime</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The no-go decay is initiated by cleavage of the mRNA close to the stall site</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The normal turnover of mRNAs has been extensively analysed in budding yeast</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>These proteins are related to translation factors , which regulate translation through direct contact with the ribosome</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>These then program large, RNA–protein complexes called ribosomes to synthesize a specific protein by &quot;translation&quot;</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>This break generates entry sites for enzymes that degrade the remainder of the RNA: the free 5′ end is degraded by Xrn1, and the 3′ end is degraded by a complex termed the exosome ( Fig. 1 )</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>This can then be dealt with by the bacterium&apos;s non-stop decay pathway, which releases the stalled ribosome and degrades the problematic mRNA</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>This triggers rapid degradation by Xrn1 and the exosome, hinting that a mechanism similar to no-go decay might operate in the flies</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>To adjust mRNA levels, cells must be able to rapidly get rid of normal mRNAs that were previously synthesized (turnover)</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Two further pathways deal only with quality control, specifically degrading mRNAs with structural defects. &quot;Nonsense-mediated decay&quot; recognizes mRNAs where the site of translation termination occurs too early in the RNA</otmi:snippet>
            </otmi:snippets>
          </otmi:section>
        </otmi:section>
        <otmi:figure>
